title: Connector or SearchProvider: indeed Search
body:
Indeed is a resume/job search engine. Ideally, we'd like to create SearchProviders for both jobs and resumes. It's likely that resume searching requires some sort of token.

Indeed API documentation is here: https://docs.indeed.com/

title: Connector: Google Suite
body:
G-Suitewill require fairly extensive work to add OAUTH2 support. It is advised to start by looking at the Microsoft Graph implementation starting in `swirl.connectors.microsoft_graph` ...

This can be done in two ways. #1 by individually integrating APIs like Gmail, Gcal, etc, or #2 using Cloud Search. We recommend initally using cloud search. 

The API is documented here: https://developers.google.com/cloud-search

title: Connector: qdrant
body:
Qdrant is a vector database & vector similarity search engine. It deploys as an API service providing search for the nearest high-dimensional vectors. With Qdrant, embeddings or neural network encoders can be turned into full-fledged applications for matching, searching, recommending, and much more!

API documentation is here: https://qdrant.github.io/qdrant/redoc/index.html

title: Create vespa.json
body:
Implemented Vespa Search
Associated issue #692

To utilize this functionality, follow these steps:

Start Vespa Instance:
Ensure you have a running Vespa instance. If not, refer to Vespa's official documentation for installation instructions.

Add JSON File to Swirl Configuration:
Insert the provided JSON file into your Swirl configuration file.

Restart Swirl:
Restart Swirl to apply the changes.

Now, you can start searching for Vespa content. Use the following command:

swirl search vespa "my query"

title: Gitpod Integration
body:
gitpod.yml file created for gitpod integration

## Description
.gitpod.yml file created for gitpod integration. As we need to run `docker-compose pull && docker-compose up` command to start server before, now using gitpod tasks, we are able to run above command automatically


## Related Issue(s)
Closes #714 

## Screenshots (if appropriate):

Add https://gitpod.io/# at the start of github swirl-search repo url which is https://github.com/swirlai/swirl-search after which I looks something like this https://gitpod.io/#https://github.com/swirlai/swirl-search and hit enter.

You will see something like this:

![image](https://github.com/swirlai/swirl-search/assets/62489114/2dd2f8c4-87dd-4236-ac5a-73e2e419fa62)

After which Dev server will start running automatically as shown below

![image](https://github.com/swirlai/swirl-search/assets/62489114/9ca3f390-b461-4b44-82ea-08f6aeacdc38)

Now create .env file as shown below and paste this line `ALLOWED_HOSTS=localhost,127.0.0.1,*`

![image](https://github.com/swirlai/swirl-search/assets/62489114/a67ad3bb-bde2-4a27-b5e6-f099cdf9a740)


Open docker-compose.yaml file and add below lines
```
    env_file:
      - .env
```
after which it looks something like this

![image](https://github.com/swirlai/swirl-search/assets/62489114/8b99aad7-1c6b-4f08-84ef-d88bd6f9b4ad)

The end result

![image](https://github.com/swirlai/swirl-search/assets/62489114/9ac82570-7e4b-4bf1-9742-b73f84e3d68f)


## Documentation
This line should be added in readme.md so that on clicking this button user will be able to easily create a workspace of swirl instead of changing url
[![Open in Gitpod](https://gitpod.io/button/open-in-gitpod.svg)](https://gitpod.io/#https://github.com/swirlai/swirl-search)

title: Create trello.json
body:
This pull request addresses Issue https://github.com/swirlai/swirl-search/issues/690 and introduces Trello as a new search provider in SwirlAI. With this enhancement, users will now be able to seamlessly integrate Trello boards into their search results, providing a more comprehensive and streamlined search experience.
Changes Made:
Implemented Trello API integration to fetch search results.
Added functionality to parse and display Trello cards within search results.
Enhanced user interface to accommodate Trello-specific information, such as board names and card details.
To run the trello provider add
"searchproviders": { "trello": { "type": "trello.TrelloSearchProvider", "api_key": "YOUR_API_KEY", "api_token": "YOUR_API_TOKEN", } }
to your Swirl Configuration file and restart Swirl and start searching for the Trello content.

title: Update fix_csv.py
body:
I've made the following changes to the code:

Simplified Function Structure:

Removed the main function and replaced it with a single function called fix_csv. Added Exception Handling:

Incorporated a try...except block to handle potential errors that might occur during file operations or CSV processing. Streamlined File Handling:

Utilized the with open(...) as ... statement to automatically handle file opening and closing. This helps improve code readability and ensures that files are closed properly, even if an error occurs. Condensed Argument Parsing:

Integrated the argument parsing directly into the __main__ block, avoiding the need for a separate function for argument parsing. Removed Redundant Checks:

Eliminated redundant checks for file existence and file extension, as these checks were already handled implicitly during file opening. Improved Output Message:

Adjusted the output message to provide more concise and clear information about the operation. This condensed version maintains the original functionality while reducing unnecessary code complexity. It should be easier to read and maintain.

title: Add support for Ollama, Palm, Claude-2, Cohere, Replicate Llama2, CodeLlama, Hugging Face (100+LLMs) - using LiteLLM
body:
This PR adds support for the above mentioned LLMs using LiteLLM https://github.com/BerriAI/litellm/ 
LiteLLM is a lightweight package to simplify LLM API calls - use any llm as a drop in replacement for gpt-3.5-turbo. 

Example
```python
from litellm import completion

## set ENV variables
os.environ["OPENAI_API_KEY"] = "openai key"
os.environ["COHERE_API_KEY"] = "cohere key"

messages = [{ "content": "Hello, how are you?","role": "user"}]

# openai call
response = completion(model="gpt-3.5-turbo", messages=messages)

# cohere call
response = completion(model="command-nightly", messages)

# anthropic call
response = completion(model="claude-instant-1", messages=messages)
```

Connector: Vespa
body:
Vespa.ai is a big data serving engine that allows you to apply AI to your data online, at any scale, with great performance. It is an open-source platform that provides a fully-featured search engine and vector database. It supports vector search (ANN), lexical search, and search in structured data, all in the same query. Integrated machine-learned model inference allows you to apply AI to make sense of your data in real-time to solve problems such as structured, text, and vector search, and real-time recommendation, personalization, and targeting. 

Documentation is here: https://docs.vespa.ai/en/api.html

The query API is defined here: https://docs.vespa.ai/en/query-api.html and detailed here: https://docs.vespa.ai/en/reference/query-api-reference.html

title: Connector: Trello
body:
Trello is a visual collaboration tool that creates a shared perspective for teams to organize, prioritize, and manage projects through customizable boards, lists, and cards. Inspired by the kanban system, Trello facilitates task tracking and project management with its drag-and-drop interface, allowing users to easily move tasks (cards) through different stages, assign responsibilities, set deadlines, and attach files. It is part of Atlassian now.

Trello does have APIs: https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/trello/rest/api-group-actions/#api-group-actions

The search API is here: https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/trello/rest/api-group-search/#api-group-search 

This looks like a typical REST API that returns JSON, so it may be easy to make a SearchProvider that configures RequestsGet to search Trello content. Look at the Atlassian connectors as a starting point: https://github.com/swirlai/swirl-search/blob/main/SearchProviders/atlassian.json

title: Connector: Discord
body:
Discord is a communication platform designed primarily for gamers that has evolved into a versatile tool for various communities and teams. It offers voice, video, and text chat channels, allowing users to connect in real-time. With features such as server creation, role-based permissions, and integrated media sharing, Discord facilitates both casual conversations and organized collaboration. Its widespread adoption stems from its user-friendly interface, diverse integrations and low cost of entry.

Discord APIs are documented here: https://discord.com/developers/docs/reference

It is not clear that Discord has a search API. There is a search interface described here: 
https://support.discord.com/hc/en-us/articles/115000468588-Using-Search 

Someone asked about this ~1 year ago, there is still no answer: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/73343722/discord-api-for-search-channels-and-messages

Maybe there is an answer in one of these articles? 
https://www.reddit.com/r/discordapp/comments/uah55h/searchcord_a_project_to_archive_discord_servers/ 
https://stateful.com/blog/discord-rest-api

title: Connector: Algolia
body:
Algolia is a cloud-based search engine that provides businesses with search experiences. It enables websites and applications to quickly implement and optimize search functionalities, ensuring users can easily find and access information within the app.

API documentation for Algolia is here: https://www.algolia.com/doc/rest-api/search/

A good starting point would be a basic search. It appears Algolia supports both HTTP GET and POST for querying: https://www.algolia.com/doc/rest-api/search/#search-endpoints

It might be that a full Connector is not required, only a SearchProvider configuring the RequestsGet or RequestsPost connector.

title: Connector: Asana
body:
Asana is a web and mobile application that "makes it easier for your team to do more work that matters" - specifically, it helps organize, track, and manage work. Asana combines elements of project management, task tracking, and collaboration tools. 

Asana has a well formed API documented here: https://developers.asana.com/reference/rest-api-reference

A straightforward first step might be to build a SearchProvider that targets Asana tasks. This would use the gettasks API call as noted here: https://developers.asana.com/reference/gettasks

A good starting point would be the Atlassian SearchProvider for Issues which is here: https://github.com/swirlai/swirl-search/blob/main/SearchProviders/atlassian.json
